prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: HCN
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: In this science goal, we propose a pilot study of three individual CO-bright giant molecular clouds in dense gas tracers, most importantly HCN(1-0).

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Here we propose dense-gas tracing observations of 3 individual giant molecular clouds with HII regions that have been detected as bright CO sources in our APEX program (selected from the sample of Deharveng et al. 1988).
Sensitivity
In the determination of the necessary integration time for the HCN observations, we assume an interferometric flux density ratio of CO(2-1) to HCN(1-0) of roughly 10:1 (e.g., Downes et al. (1992) where the CO(1-0)/HCN(1-0) line ratios range from 5 to 9). The interferometric results by Downes et al. (1992) are probing spatial scales (20 pc) that come close to those that we intend to probe in this experiment. The sources that we propose to observe in HCN(1-0) have expected interferometric CO detections brighter than 1.2 Jy/beam, and we thus expect an HCN flux density of 0.12 Jy/beam. To have room for different HCN/CO ratios, we propose a target S/N of 30 at a velocity resolution of 1 km s^{-1}; the required rms thus is 4 mJy. Three sources can be observed in a total time of 1.42 h. We still expect the 10:1 estimate to be conservative since 1) we are comparing CO(2-1) to HCN(1-0) and not the 1-0 transitions, and 2) NGC 300 is a low-metallicity environment where modeling suggests that the CO/HCN ratio is reduced (Rosolowsky et al. 2011). The setup also includes the dense-gas tracers HCO+(1-0) and CS(2-1) as well as a continuum band.
Imaging
In the HCN observations, we need arcsecond-resolution observations and also sensitivity to extended structures. Assuming sizes of giant molecular clouds of less than 100 pc, we expect to see maximum angular scales of 10" at the distance of NGC 300. We thus propose to use the C34-5 configuration for the HCN observations (0.75" angular resolution and 14.4" maximum recoverable scale). Simulations show that even with short observations, the uv coverage is sufficient to map the source structure. The synthesized beam sizes in our proposed observations correspond to scales of about 6.9 pc where the primary beam corresponds to 630 pc (HCN). The maximum recoverable scale corresponds to 133 pc, above the expected ~100 pc scales of giant molecular clouds.
Correlator setup
We expect line widths of up to 10 km s^{-1}, and a velocity resolution of 1 km s^{-1} is sufficient for our purposes. The HCN setup covers HCN(1-0), HCO+(1-0), and CS(2-1) as well as a continuum band. To limit the data rate, the spectral windows have reduced bandwidths which are, however, sufficient for our purposes. Most importantly, HCN(1-0) will be covered with a Hanning-smoothed resolution of 0.413 km s^{-1} and a spectral window of 397 km s^{-1}. The CS(2-1) and the HCO+(1-0) transitions are covered with similar resolution and bandwidth. Detections in the additional bands are not a goal of this proposal, even though detections seem feasible for the brightest sources. However, this setup makes optimal use of the ALMA capabilities. To increase observing efficiency, we have selected a setup with a velocity range that easily includes the velocities of all our targets (they span ~140 km s^{-1}) so that no retuning is required.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: CO
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: In this science goal, we propose to obtain high-resolution CO(2-1) observations of 42 individual giant molecular clouds with single-dish (APEX) CO detections and six non-detections in an attempt to probe lower masses and the effect of the beam-filling factor.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Here we propose CO(2-1) observations of 42 individual giant molecular clouds with HII regions that have been detected in our APEX program (selected from the sample of Deharveng et al. 1988). Additionally, this sample includes 6 CO non-detections with high infrared luminosities. These non-detections may have been missed due to beam dilution in the single-dish data.
Sensitivity
The antenna temperatures of CO in our APEX cloud sample correspond to a flux density range from 4.5 Jy/beam down to 0.5 Jy/beam. First SMA results indicate tentatively that about half of this flux will be recovered on arcsecond scales. We propose short observations down to a sensitivity of 8 mJy (S/N~30) at a velocity resolution of 1 km s^{-1}. The total sample of 48 targets will take 3.94h to complete. There may be enough sensitivity to potentially also detect C18O which is included in the same setup, as is a continuum band.
Imaging
In the CO observations, we need arcsecond-resolution observations and also some sensitivity to extended structures. Assuming sizes of giant molecular clouds of less than 100 pc, we expect to see maximum angular scales of 10" at the distance of NGC 300. We thus propose to use the C34-2 configuration for the CO observation (0.89" angular resolution and 11.4" maximum recoverable scale). Simulations show that even with short observations, the uv coverage is sufficient to map the source structure. The synthesized beam sizes in our proposed observations correspond to scales of about 8.2 pc where the primary beam corresponds to 240 pc. The maximum recoverable scale corresponds to 105 pc, above the expected ~100 pc scales of giant molecular clouds.
Correlator setup
We expect line widths of up to 10 km s^{-1}, and a velocity resolution of 1 km s^{-1} is sufficient for our purposes. The CO(2-1) line will be covered with a Hanning-smoothed resolution of 0.318 km s^{-1} and a spectral window of 610 km s^{-1}. To increase observing efficiency, we have selected a setup with a velocity range that easily includes the velocities of all our targets (they span ~140 km s^{-1}) so that no retuning is required. Additionally included in the setup are the C18O line and a continuum band. We emphasize that detections in these additional bands are not a goal of this proposal, even though detections seem feasible for the brightest sources. However, this setup makes optimal use of the ALMA capabilities.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: A little more than a half-century ago, Schmidt conjectured a power-law scaling relation between the star formation rate and interstellar gas surface densities in galaxies. Much of our understanding of extragalactic star formation is based on this scaling law. However, recent studies of galactic GMCs indicate that our understanding of the Schmidt law may need to undergo serious revision. These studies demonstrate that there is no Schmidt scaling law that relates the SFR and gas surface densities between galactic GMCs. Consequently the empirically derived Schmidt scaling relation for disk galaxies is likely an artifact of unresolved measurements of extragalactic GMCs and not a result of an underlying physical law of star formation. Here we propose to extend our MW studies with an ALMA CO survey and pilot HCN observations of the GMC population in the nearby disk galaxy NGC 300 to: 1) assess the extent to which the physical process of star formation operating in local MW clouds describes the star formation in NGC300, 2) critically test the nature of the Schmidt law in an external star forming environment and 3) bridge the gap between galactic and extragalactic star formation studies.
